Reasoning: The paper discusses improvements to the decoding of low-density parity-check codes, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT). The proposed modifications to the flipping function and flipped bit selection rule involve tracking the evolutions of check and variable nodes' reliabilities, which could be related to network information theory (cs.NI) or social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper also discusses selective weight-updating schedules, which could be related to data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) or control systems (cs.SY).
